<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" src="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/2025-06-08-mementos.jpg" alt="https://www.reddit.com/r/BeAmazed/comments/1igjigr/leonce_evrard_is_a_skilled_marble_worker_he_was/" width="1080" height="766" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-70914" srcset="https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/2025-06-08-mementos.jpg 1080w, https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/2025-06-08-mementos-600x426.jpg 600w, https://www.futilitycloset.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/2025-06-08-mementos-300x213.jpg 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 1080px) 100vw, 1080px" /></p>
<p>At midday each June 21, a shaft of light pierces the roof of a mausoleum in Brussels&#8217; Laeken Cemetery and creates a heart of light.</p>
<p>It&#8217;s not clear whether this was deliberate. The tomb&#8217;s occupants, Louise Flignot and LÃ©once Evrard, died in 1916 and 1919, and the mausoleum was not built until 1920. Its designer, one Georges deLarabrie, is not known to have produced any other work, and the planning documents don&#8217;t mention the heart.</p>
<p>When Sir Lawrence Tanfield died in 1625, his wife composed this <a href="https://archive.org/details/englishchurchmon0000esda/page/132/mode/2up">inscription</a> for their joint monument at Burford in Oxfordshire:</p>
<p>Here shadows lie<br />
Whilst earth is sadd,<br />
Still hopes to die<br />
To him she hadd.<br />
In bliss is hee<br />
Whom I loved best;<br />
Thrice happy shee<br />
With him to rest.</p>
<p>So shall I bee<br />
With him I loved,<br />
And he with mee<br />
And both us blessed.<br />
Love made me poet,<br />
And this I writt;<br />
My heart did do it,<br />
And not my wit.</p>
